article.description: Devin Harris scored 16 points and Wisconsin (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 17 AP) survived a late rally by Iowa to hold on to first place in the Big Ten with a 54-52 victory Wednesday night.
article.headline: Harris scores 16 in road win
article.linkText: Wisconsin holds off Iowa, stays atop Big Ten
article.story: IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Devin Harris saw the shot go up and felt his stomach sink. Surely, the Wisconsin guard thought, it was going in and Iowa would win. But Jeff Horner's 3-point attempt bounced off the rim at the buzzer and Wisconsin (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 17 AP) escaped with a 54-52 victory on Wednesday night, keeping the Badgers in first place in the Big Ten. "Where was my heart? I don't think you want to know," Harris said with a laugh. "It was in my stomach. It looked good to me, but fortunately it fell off." Harris scored 16 points to lead Wisconsin (16-4, 7-2), which hit a rut offensively after building a 13-point lead early in the second half and was hanging on at the end. Still, after the Badgers were embarrassed in a 69-51 loss at Northwestern on Saturday, this win was as good as a rout. "Things got away from us against Northwestern," Wisconsin coach Bo Ryan said. "You need to get it back. You can't get down. These guys just prepared Monday and Tuesday. The effort was there." So was Iowa's at the end. The Hawkeyes (12-9, 5-5) got within two points on Glen Worley's 3-pointer with 43 seconds left, then had a chance to win it when Wisconsin's Zach Morley missed a jump hook with 10 seconds remaining. Iowa's Pierre Pierce started to drive, then passed to Horner on the right wing. Horner, who made the winning shot in a double-overtime victory at Indiana on Saturday, had a good look at the basket and his shot appeared to be on line, but the ball bounced away. Horner, Worley, Pierce and teammate Greg Brunner all collapsed to the floor when the buzzer sounded. "I thought it felt really good," Horner said. "Unfortunately, it was a little short. It's very frustrating. You get a good look after the double on (Pierce) and it's frustrating not to hit it." Clayton Hanson added 12 points for Wisconsin, all on 3-pointers, and Mike Wilkinson had 12 points and nine rebounds. Pierce led Iowa with 20 points, while Brunner had 10 points and 13 rebounds. "I think we did pretty good on defense, forced them to take a lot of outside shots," Wisconsin's Maurice "Boo" Wade said. "Pierce was able to slash to the basket a lot. He made a lot of good moves down low. He made some great shots for them, but we came away with the victory so it was great for us." Wade returned from a two-game suspension imposed after he was accused of choking a female friend. He was formally charged with misdemeanor battery earlier Wednesday. "The team was really 100 percent," said Wade, who had four points, four rebounds and two assists. "When I got there, they welcomed me. It was a great thing, but then again it was a bad thing what happened." With crisp passing and cutting against Iowa's 2-3 zone, Wisconsin opened a 32-25 halftime lead and appeared to be in control early in the second half. Harris and Wilkinson each hit a 3-pointer in an 8-0 run that gave Wisconsin a 42-29 lead with 15:31 left. At that point, Pierce was the only offensive threat for Iowa, scoring the Hawkeyes' first 10 points of the second half. His teammates then started to get involved and Iowa slowed the Badgers when it switched to man-to-man on defense, holding Wisconsin to 12 points over the final 15{ minutes. "We got a little trigger happy outside and they made some big 3s to cut the lead down," Harris said. The Hawkeyes made their final run after Harris' layup gave Wisconsin a 52-44 lead with 4:03 to play. Pierce scored on a putback and Brody Boyd hit a 3 to cut the lead to 52-49. Harris' 5-foot bank shot made it 54-49 with 1:25 remaining and Iowa's hopes appeared to end when Pierce stumbled as he started a drive to the basket and was called for traveling. But a traveling call against Harris gave the ball back to the Hawkeyes and Worley buried his 3 from the left wing, cutting the lead to 54-52. Moments later, Horner was squaring up -- and missing. "The guys did a tremendous job and we got a great look," Iowa coach Steve Alford said. "If we had to design the thing up again, that's who we'd want to take it."
